---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { costPillars, operatingLoop } from "../facts";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="How it works · Squeezy"
  description="How Squeezy prepares local code context, keeps conversations compact, sends focused work to the model, and tracks token spend."
  active="how"
>
  <section class="page-hero">
    <div class="page-hero-inner">
      <span class="eyebrow">how it works</span>
      <h1>Prepare locally. Ask the model with focus.</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Squeezy is built around a simple loop: understand the repo locally,
        gather the relevant context, keep the conversation tight, and send the
        model a smaller, better-shaped task.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="flow">
      {
        operatingLoop.map((item) => (
          <article class="flow-step">
            <span>{item.label}</span>
            <strong>{item.title}</strong>
            <p>{item.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section band">
    <div class="section-header wide">
      <span class="eyebrow">cost controls</span>
      <h2>The loop is supported by several independent savings.</h2>
      <p>
        Local code understanding is only one part. Squeezy also shapes tool
        output, reuses stable prompt context when possible, compacts older
        conversation state, isolates exploration, and routes simple turns
        through cheaper paths.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-3">
      {
        costPillars.slice(0, 6).map((fact) => (
          <article class="card">
            <span class="label">{fact.label}</span>
            <h3>{fact.title}</h3>
            <p>{fact.body}</p>
          </article>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="grid-2">
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">fallbacks</span>
        <h3>It still uses ordinary tools when that is the right path.</h3>
        <p>
          Some tasks are best answered by search, a focused file read, a build,
          a test, or a verifier command. Squeezy should spend local work where
          it helps, not force one navigation path onto every task.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <span class="label">visibility</span>
        <h3>The bill is something you can inspect.</h3>
        <p>
          Token accounting and context views make provider usage, cache hits,
          tool output, subagent work, and estimates visible instead of treating
          spend as a black box.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
